<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<worksheet xml:id="gaussian-elimination">
  <title>Gaussian elimination</title>

  <p><alert>MTH 204:  January 15</alert></p>

  <introduction>
    <p>In this activity, we will develop an algorithm that transforms
    a system of linear equations into a specific form, called
    <term>reduced row echelon form</term>, that allows us to instantly
    draw conclusions about the set of solutions.</p>
  </introduction>
  
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p workspace="1in">
      Suppose we have a linear system whose augmented matrix is
      <md>
        \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
        \right]
      </md>
      What does this tell us about the set of solutions to the linear
      system? Is there 0, 1, or infinitely many solutions?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>If the variables are <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m>, we know
    that <m>x=-2</m>, <m>y=4</m>, and <m>z=1</m>.  Therefore, there is
    exactly one solution.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let's consider this linear system.
      <md>
        \begin{alignedat}{4}
          x \amp  {}+{}  \amp y \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2z \amp  {}={}  \amp 1 \\
          2x \amp  {}-{}  \amp y \amp  {}-{}  \amp 2z \amp  {}={}  \amp 2 \\
          -x \amp  {}+{}  \amp y \amp  {}+{}  \amp z \amp  {}={}  \amp 0 \\
        \end{alignedat}
      </md>
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Write this system as an augmented matrix.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
          2 \amp -1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \\
          -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
          \end{array}\right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For the first step in the Gaussian elimination algorithm, we
        would like to make the entry in the second row and first column
        a <q>0</q>. You can do this by performing a row replacement
        operation, multiplying row 1 by -2 and adding it to row
        2. Sometimes, people write this as <m>-2R_1 + R_2 \to R_2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp -3 \amp -6 \amp 0 \\
          -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
          \end{array}\right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For the second step, we would like to make the entry in the
        third row and first column a <q>0</q>. Determine the row
        replacement operation you would use and then perform that
        operation.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We can use <m>R_1+R_3\to R_3</m> and obtain
        <md>
          \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp -3 \amp -6 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}\right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        OK, good. We have essentially eliminated <m>x</m> from the
        second and third equation. You have some choice in what comes
        next, but it might be convenient to make the entry in the second
        row, second column a <q>1</q>. How would you scale the second
        row (i.e. multiply it by a nonzero number) to produce a <q>1</q>
        in that position? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p> Scaling the second row by <m>-1/3</m> gives
        <md>
          \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}\right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The next step would be to produce a <q>0</q> in the third row,
        second column. How can you do that? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p> We perform <m>-2R_2+R_3\to R_3</m> so that
        <md>
          \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
          1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}\right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task workspace="3in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        From this point, how can you finish the Gaussian elimination
        algorithm to find the solution to the original linear system? Be
        specific about naming each step of the algorithm.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p> 
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
            \end{array}\right] \amp \sim
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What can you say about the set of solutions to this linear
        system? Is there 0, 1, or infinitely many solutions? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>There is exactly one solution:  <m>x=1</m>, <m>y=2</m>, and
      <m>z=-1</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p workspace="3.8in">
      Rewrite the following linear system as an augmented matrix and
      find the solution using Gaussian elimination.
      <md>
        \begin{alignedat}{4}
          x \amp  {}+{}  \amp 2y \amp  {}{}  \amp  \amp  {}={}  \amp 2 \\
          -x \amp  {}{}  \amp  \amp  {}-{}  \amp 4z \amp  {}={}  \amp -6 \\
          2x \amp  {}+{}  \amp 4y \amp  {}+{}  \amp z \amp  {}={}  \amp 7 \\
        \end{alignedat}
      </md>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>We set up an augmented matrix and apply row operations so that
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            -1 \amp 0 \amp -4 \amp -6 \\
            2 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 7 \\
            \end{array}\right] \amp \sim
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 2 \amp -4 \amp -4 \\
            2 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 7 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 2 \amp -4 \amp -4 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp -2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp \sim 
            \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -6 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
            \end{array}\right]
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>We will make a few observations about situations that
    frequently occur.</p>
  </introduction>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What does the equation <m>0x+0y=0</m> tell us, if anything,
        about the values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>It doesn't tell us anything since any values of <m>x</m> and
      <m>y</m> cause the equation to be true.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose that you have a linear system in the variables <m>x</m>
        and <m>y</m> whose augmented matrix is as below. Describe the
        solution space in as much detail as possible.
        <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{rr|r}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 
          0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 
          0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
          \end{array}
          \right].
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>We can ignore the last row and note that <m>x=3</m> and
      <m>y=0</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p workspace="1in">
      Suppose that you have a linear system in the variables <m>x</m>
      and <m>y</m> whose augmented matrix is as below. Describe the
      solution space in as much detail as possible. 
      <md>
        \left[
          \begin{array}{rr|r}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
        \right].
      </md>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>The last row implies that <m>0x+0y=1</m>.  However, there are
    no values for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> that cause this equation to be
    true.  This system therefore has no solutions.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The goal of Gaussian elimination is to create an augmented
      matrix that is in <em>reduced row echelon form</em>, which means  
      <ul>
        <li>If the entries in a row are all zero, then the same is
        true of any row below it.</li> 
        <li>If we move across a row from left to right, the first
        nonzero entry we encounter is 1. We call this entry the
        <em>leading entry</em> in the row.</li> 
        <li>The leading entry in any row is to the right of the
        leading entries in all the rows above it.</li> 
        <li>A leading entry is the only nonzero entry in its
        column.</li> 
      </ul>
      Consider each of the matrices below and determine whether it is
      in reduced row echelon form or not. If not, perform a sequence
      of row operations to find a reduced row echelon form. Then use
      that form to determine whether the system has 0, 1, or
      infinitely many solutions. 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="0.5in">
        <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>This is in reduced row echelon form.</p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="0.75in">
        <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>This is not in reduced row echelon form because there are
      nonzero elements in the columns that have leading entries.
      <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]\sim
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]\
          \sim\left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
          0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
      </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="0.75in">
        <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp -8 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>We scale the first row by <m>1/2</m> so that
        <md>
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp -8 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
          \sim
          \left[
          \begin{array}{ccc|c}
          1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp -4 \\
          0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
          \end{array}
          \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p workspace="1in">
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc|c}
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>We can interchange rows so that
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc|c}
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
            \sim
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p workspace="1in">
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The last row has a leading entry but there are nonzero
        elements above it:
          <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
            \sim
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

<exercise>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="1in">
        Create, if possible, an augmented matrix in reduced row echelon
        form that represents a linear system having three equations, two
        variables, and exactly one solution. If this is not possible,
        state the reason why. 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{cc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp  2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp  0 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="1in">
        Create, if possible, an augmented matrix in reduced row echelon
        form that represents a linear system having four equations, two
        variables, and no solutions. If this is not possible, state the
        reason why. 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{cc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="1in">
        Create, if possible, an augmented matrix in reduced row echelon
        form that represents a linear system having two equations, four
        variables, and exactly one solution. If this is not possible,
        state the reason why. 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>This is not possible since there will always be free variables:
        <md>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{cccc|c}
            1 \amp 0 \amp * \amp * \amp -1 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp * \amp 2 \\
            \end{array}
            \right]
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>      
  </task>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="1in">
        If an augmented matrix is in reduced row echelon form, what does
        a row whose entries are all zero tell us about the set of
        solutions? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>It doesn't tell us anything since any value for the
      variables will work.</p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p workspace="1in">
        How can you quickly determine if a linear system has no
        solutions by looking at the reduced row echelon form of its
        augmented matrix? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>If there is a leading entry in the last column, that equation
      is telling us that <m>0=1</m>, which cannot be true.  Therefore,
      there are no solutions.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
</exercise>

<assemblage>
  <p>Make sure you can answer the following questions:
  <ul>
    <li>What are the three row operations we can perform on an
    augmented matrix without changing the solutions to the system of
    linear equations?</li> 
    <li>How does the Gaussian elimination algorithm work?</li> 
    <li>What is the reduced row echelon of a matrix?</li>
    <li>How does the reduced row echelon form of an augmented matrix
    tell us when there are no solutions?</li> 
    <li>What does a row of all zeroes in the reduced row echelon form
    of an augmented matrix tell us about the solutions?</li> 
  </ul>
  </p>
</assemblage>

</worksheet>
